'''Augustus''' ({{lang-la|[[Imperator]] [[Caesar (title)|Caesar]] [[Divi filius]] [[Augustus (honorific)|Augustus]]}};{{#tag:ref|Classical Latin spelling and [[Latin spelling and pronunciation|reconstructed Classical Latin pronunciation]] of the names of Augustus:
# {{sqc|GAIVS OCTAVIVS}}<br />{{IPA-la|ˈɡaːɪ.ʊs ɔkˈtaːwɪ.ʊs|IPA}}
# {{sqc|GAIVS IVLIVS CAESAR OCTAVIANVS}}<br />{{IPA-la|ˈɡaːɪ.ʊs ˈjuːlɪ.ʊs ˈkae̯sar ɔktaːwɪˈaːnʊs|IPA}}
# {{sqc|IMPERATOR CAESAR DIVI F(ILIVS) AVGVSTVS}}<br />{{IPA-la|ɪmpɛˈraːtɔr ˈkae̯sar ˈdiːwiː ˈfiːlɪ.ʊs au̯ˈɡʊstʊs|IPA}}
The spelling {{sqc|AGVSTVS}}, indicating the pronunciation {{IPA-la|aˈɡʊstʊs|}}, occurs in inscriptions ({{Harvnb|Allen|1965|p=61}})|group="nb"}} 23 September 63 BC – 19 August AD 14) was a [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] statesman and military leader who became the first [[Roman emperor|emperor]] of the [[Roman Empire]], reigning from 27 BC until his death in AD 14.{{#tag:ref|The dates of his rule are contemporary dates; Augustus lived under two calendars, the [[Roman calendar|Roman Republican]] until 45 BC, and [[Julian calendar|the Julian]] after 45 BC. Due to departures from [[Julius Caesar]]'s intentions, Augustus finished restoring the Julian calendar in March AD 4, and the correspondence between the proleptic Julian calendar and the calendar observed in Rome is uncertain before 8 BC. (Blackburn & Holford-Strevens 2003: 670–1)|group="nb"}} His status as the founder of the [[Roman Principate]] has consolidated [[Augustan reform|an enduring legacy]] as one of the most effective and controversial leaders in human history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Augustus-Roman-emperor|title=Augustus {{!}} Biography, Accomplishments, Full Name, & Facts|work=Encyclopædia Britannica|access-date=6 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.com/topics/ancient-history/emperor-augustus|title=Augustus - Ancient History - HISTORY.com|website=HISTORY.com|access-date=6 March 2018}}</ref> The reign of Augustus initiated an era of relative peace known as the ''[[Pax Romana]]''. The Roman world was largely free from large-scale conflict for more than two centuries, despite continuous wars of imperial expansion on the Empire's frontiers and the year-long civil war known as the "[[Year of the Four Emperors]]" over the imperial succession.

Augustus was born '''Gaius Octavius''' into an old and wealthy [[equites|equestrian branch]] of the [[plebs|plebeian]] [[Octavia (gens)|''gens'' Octavia]]. His maternal great-uncle [[Julius Caesar]] was [[assassination of Julius Caesar|assassinated]] in 44 BC, and Octavius was named in Caesar's will as his [[Adoption in ancient Rome|adopted]] son and heir. Along with [[Mark Antony]] and [[Marcus Aemilius Lepidus (triumvir)|Marcus Lepidus]], he formed the [[Second Triumvirate]] to defeat the assassins of Caesar. Following their victory at the [[Battle of Philippi]], the Triumvirate divided the [[Roman Republic]] among themselves and ruled as ''de facto'' [[Roman dictator|dictators]]. The Triumvirate was eventually torn apart by the competing ambitions of its members. Lepidus was driven into exile and stripped of his position, and Antony committed suicide following his defeat at the [[Battle of Actium]] by Octavian in 31 BC.

After the demise of the Second Triumvirate, Augustus restored the outward façade of the free Republic, with governmental power vested in the [[Roman Senate]], the [[Roman magistrate|executive magistrates]], and the [[Roman assemblies|legislative assemblies]]. In reality, however, he retained his autocratic power over the Republic. By law, Augustus held a collection of powers granted to him for life by the Senate, including [[commander-in-chief|supreme military command]], and those of [[tribune]] and [[Roman censor|censor]]. It took several years for Augustus to develop the framework within which a formally republican state could be led under his sole rule. He rejected monarchical titles, and instead called himself ''[[Princeps]] Civitatis'' ("First Citizen"). The resulting [[Constitution of the Roman Empire|constitutional framework]] became known as the Principate, the [[History of the Roman Empire|first phase of the Roman Empire]].

Augustus dramatically enlarged the Empire, annexing [[Egypt (Roman province)|Egypt]], [[Dalmatia (Roman province)|Dalmatia]], [[Pannonia]], [[Noricum]], and [[Raetia]], expanding possessions in [[Africa (Roman province)|Africa]], and completing the conquest of [[Hispania]], but suffered a [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest|major setback]] in [[Germania]]. Beyond the frontiers, he secured the Empire with a buffer region of [[client state]]s and made peace with the [[Parthian Empire]] through diplomacy. He reformed the Roman system of taxation, developed [[Roman roads|networks of roads]] with an [[cursus publicus|official courier system]], established a [[standing army]], established the [[Praetorian Guard]], created official [[cohortes urbanae|police]] and [[vigiles|fire-fighting services]] for Rome, and rebuilt much of the city during his reign. Augustus died in AD 14 at the age of 75, probably from natural causes. However, there were unconfirmed rumors that his wife [[Livia]] poisoned him. He was succeeded as emperor by his adopted son (also stepson and former son-in-law) [[Tiberius]].

